    {
        "user": "U0887QU9G2V",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1769460322.969859",
        "client_msg_id": "39e6f413-67a5-4279-9f1a-9be936a7e895",
        "text": "Hi <@U05GSC0B4A0>! Arriving late to the party. Interesting to read what you’re working on!\n\n&gt;  I’ve been playing around with this idea of taking some of the core original ideas of OO\/Smalltalk (Objects as self contained computers that pass messages with binding at late as possible) and seeing what we could do if we added an LLM in there\nI am working on <http:\/\/github.com\/altocodenl\/cell|cell>, which is a programming substrate where every call can be considered as a computer or agent: a call receives a message and produces a response. When the call needs to make other calls, it does all the binding at runtime.\n\nEach call is its own frame of reference. I think Paul’s work is definitely in that direction as well.\n\nI also envision (because I’m still implementing the basics) that deterministic calls can make LLM calls, and viceversa. And because it’s all text with the same format, it should be quite flowing.",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_profile": {
            "avatar_hash": "6b9d24756ac1",
            "image_72": "https:\/\/avatars.slack-edge.com\/2025-01-08\/8269664865108_6b9d24756ac1aa304bb9_72.jpg",
            "first_name": "Federico",
            "real_name": "Federico Pereiro",
            "display_name": "Federico Pereiro",
            "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
            "name": "fpereiro",
            "is_restricted": false,
            "is_ultra_restricted": false
        },
        "thread_ts": "1767636991.559059",
        "parent_user_id": "U05GSC0B4A0",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "sKSIo",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Hi "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "user",
                                "user_id": "U05GSC0B4A0"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "! Arriving late to the party. Interesting to read what you’re working on!\n\n"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_quote",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": " I’ve been playing around with this idea of taking some of the core original ideas of OO\/Smalltalk (Objects as self contained computers that pass messages with binding at late as possible) and seeing what we could do if we added an LLM in there"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\nI am working on "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "link",
                                "url": "http:\/\/github.com\/altocodenl\/cell",
                                "text": "cell"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": ", which is a programming substrate where every call can be considered as a computer or agent: a call receives a message and produces a response. When the call needs to make other calls, it does all the binding at runtime.\n\nEach call is its own frame of reference. I think Paul’s work is definitely in that direction as well.\n\nI also envision (because I’m still implementing the basics) that deterministic calls can make LLM calls, and viceversa. And because it’s all text with the same format, it should be quite flowing."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "user": "U0887QU9G2V",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1769460578.572349",
        "client_msg_id": "dd160557-7b10-4713-bb64-81ea6227aff3",
        "text": "I wrote a short <https:\/\/federicopereiro.com\/writing-syntax\/|article> prompted by Ryan Dahl’s statement that “the era of humans writing code is over.” (I consider Ryan a living legend, BTW).\n\nI have two objections\/doubts:\n1. What if code is no longer writing “syntax”? What if code can be as readable as natural language?\n2. How are we supposed to review code if we don’t write it? Can you be an editor without being a writer? Can we consider LLMs as good enough code writers that take natural language descriptions of a system, in the same way we consider compilers “good enough” machine code generators?\nI’d like to hear what you think (or feel) about this.",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_profile": {
            "avatar_hash": "6b9d24756ac1",
            "image_72": "https:\/\/avatars.slack-edge.com\/2025-01-08\/8269664865108_6b9d24756ac1aa304bb9_72.jpg",
